{"format":"tiptap/v1","updatedAt":"2026-06-22T12:14:23.694Z","doc":{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Settings files"},{"type":"text","text":" are where Claude Code stores configuration that controls how it behaves, such as model choice, permissions, sandbox rules, and other defaults. They let you customize Claude Code once and have those preferences apply consistently instead of re-entering them every session."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"What they are"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Claude Code uses a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"layered configuration system"},{"type":"text","text":": settings can exist at the user level, project level, local-only level, and even system-managed level. The same setting can appear in more than one place, and Claude Code resolves them by priority so the most specific allowed setting wins. "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"link","attrs":{"href":"https://m.academy/lessons/settings-configuration-fallback-hierarchy-claude-code/","target":"_blank","rel":"noopener noreferrer nofollow","class":"text-brand-600 underline dark:text-brand-400","title":null}}],"text":"m"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Where they live"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Scope"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Typical location"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Effect"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"User"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"~/.claude/settings.json"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Applies across all your projects"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Project"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":".claude/settings.json"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Applies to everyone working in that repository"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Local"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":".claude/settings.local.json"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Applies only to your copy of that repo"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Managed"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"System-managed config folder"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Controlled by IT or the platform, not usually editable by you"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"What you can configure"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Settings files can control things like:\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Model selection"},{"type":"text","text":".\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Thinking behavior"},{"type":"text","text":".\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Permission defaults"},{"type":"text","text":".\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Allowed or denied commands"},{"type":"text","text":".\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Additional directories"},{"type":"text","text":" Claude may access.\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Cleanup and session behavior"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"A few common examples from the settings hierarchy include "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"model"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"language"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"cleanupPeriodDays"},{"type":"text","text":", and permission-related options such as "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"defaultMode"},{"type":"text","text":", allowlists, and denylists."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Why they matter"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Settings files are useful because they turn repeated preferences into a durable setup. Instead of saying “use this model,” “stay in plan mode,” or “don’t touch these folders” every time, you encode that policy once and Claude Code follows it across sessions. "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"link","attrs":{"href":"https://m.academy/lessons/settings-configuration-fallback-hierarchy-claude-code/","target":"_blank","rel":"noopener noreferrer nofollow","class":"text-brand-600 underline dark:text-brand-400","title":null}}],"text":"m"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"How they work"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Claude Code reads settings from multiple places and applies them in order of precedence. Higher-priority settings can override lower-priority ones, so a project can specialize behavior without changing your global defaults. That makes them useful both for personal preferences and team-wide repository rules. "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"link","attrs":{"href":"https://m.academy/lessons/settings-configuration-fallback-hierarchy-claude-code/","target":"_blank","rel":"noopener noreferrer nofollow","class":"text-brand-600 underline dark:text-brand-400","title":null}}],"text":"m"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Common mistakes"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Putting a setting in the wrong scope, then wondering why it does not apply."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Expecting a user-level setting to override a project-level rule when the project is configured more specifically."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Editing JSON with syntax errors, which prevents the file from being read correctly."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Forgetting that some enterprise-managed settings cannot be overridden."}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Mental model"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Think of settings files as "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"layers of house rules"},{"type":"text","text":": system rules first, then team rules, then your personal preferences, with the most specific permitted rule taking effect."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Key takeaways"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Settings files control Claude Code’s default behavior."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"They are layered: user, project, local, and managed. "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"link","attrs":{"href":"https://m.academy/lessons/settings-configuration-fallback-hierarchy-claude-code/","target":"_blank","rel":"noopener noreferrer nofollow","class":"text-brand-600 underline dark:text-brand-400","title":null}}],"text":"m"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"settings.json"},{"type":"text","text":" is the main place to define preferences and permissions."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Project settings are ideal for shared team behavior; local settings are ideal for personal overrides."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The most specific allowed setting usually wins."}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph"}]}}
